Each of these olive oils is pressed from just one type of olive grown in one specific region in Italy, so they sing with unique flavor. They vary in color from pale straw yellow to dark green, and have aromas of herbs, nuts, vegetables, or grasses. Olive oils can express their terroir in the same way wines do—and with a little practice, you’ll be able to taste the difference between each of these olive oils, from the North to the South of Italy! 
Read more about it here! https://giadzy.com/blogs/tips/how-different-olives-make-different-oils-and-how-to-choose-the-right-one

Every holiday season I get together with @auntraffy so we can argue about how to make Struffoli 😜 
These little fried dough balls covered in honey are a holiday tradition all around Italy. I like to mix them in with hazelnuts, although Raffy will tell you that the original recipe had just dough, no hazelnuts. However you like to make them, this is a fun and delish holiday tradition to embrace! Recipe on @thegiadzy

Bologna has some of the best Italian food (in my opinion!). It’s the birthplace of Bolognese and Mortadella, so how could you go wrong?! It’s a little slice of heaven in the Emilia-Romagna 😍

I recently met the Lazzaroni family, makers of Chiostro di Saronno Amaretti cookies, up in Northern Italy. They have been making amaretti cookies since 1719 (!!) and I was lucky enough to take a tour of their archival museum. There were so many retro amaretti cookie tins- it was a really cool site to see. I also found out they used to sell cookies to my grandfather over 30 years ago! It was a full circle, really special experience & sharing a little piece of it w/ all of u 💕

One of my lifelong dreams has become a reality and I'm soo thrilled to announce that my catering company, @giadacatering, is officially here for everyone in Southern California!

I'm thrilled that this new culinary journey has brought me full circle & will allow me to deliver unforgettable events for all of ur special moments. Whether it's an intimate gathering or a grand celebration, everyone is welcome to have a seat at my table! Buon Appetito!

The Old Fashioned is one of the most classic cocktails out there! This is my Italian spin on the drink. It usually consists of bourbon, bitters & a bit of simple syrup w/ an orange peel. My version includes my fav Northern Italian Amarena cherries & I use that delish cherry syrup instead of sugar & water. It gives the drink such a great rich sweetness & of course, you need a few of the whole cherries on a skewer to finish the drink 😍 Cin cin! 

Recipe here: https://giadzy.com/blogs/recipes/italian-old-fashioned

La Merenda is a mid-afternoon or after school snack in Italy & this is one of Jade’s favs. My fav is ricotta w/ a little cocoa powder and (a lot) of sugar, just how I had it w/ my Nonno when I was a kid ☺️

It’s Sunday sauce kind of day 😌

Recipe:
3 tablespoons olive oil 
2 shallots, chopped fine 
4 cloves garlic, chopped fine 
1 teaspoon dried oregano 
2 pounds ground chicken 
1 teaspoon salt 
2/3 cup dry white wine 
4 cups Marinara Sauce
1 pound long flat pasta such as pappardelle
1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan

Heat the oil in a heavy large skillet over medium-high heat. Add the shallots, garlic and oregano and saute until tender, about 2 minutes. Add the chicken, season with salt, and break it up with a wooden spoon. Cook until completely cooked through, continuing to break it up as you stir, for about 3 minutes. Add the wine and stir to scrape up any brown bits on the bottom of the skillet. Add the marinara sauce and bring to a simmer. Reduce the heat to medium-low and simmer gently until the flavors blend, about 10 minutes. Taste and adjust seasoning if necessary.
Meanwhile, bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add the pasta and cook until al dente, stirring occasionally, about 8 minutes. Drain, reserving 1 cup of cooking liquid. Add the pasta to the ragu and toss to coat, adding some reserved cooking liquid to moisten if needed. Transfer the pasta to a large serving bowl. Sprinkle with Parmesan and serve.
